// rev_head.su — reverse-addressing read head (Unix rung 6: rev / tac).
//
// `rev` reverses the characters within each line; `tac` reverses the order of
// whole lines. Both are PERMUTATIONS over a RAM buffer, and the permutation is
// computed on the substrate: a recurring cursor counts up 0,1,2,... and the head
// emits `pointer = limit - cursor`, so the addresses it asks the orchestrator to
// serve run DOWN from `limit` to 0 — the reverse read order. `limit` (the last
// index to read, e.g. line_length-1 for rev, or the last element index for tac)
// is passed in each tick, so the address arithmetic is a substrate subtract, not
// a host counter. The orchestrator serves RAM at each emitted address; the served
// stream is the reversed content.
//
// This mirrors text_scan.su (forward cursor -> forward order); here the same
// recurring cursor drives a reversed emission via one substrate subtraction.
function vector rev_head(vector limit) {
    recurring vector cursor = make_real(0.0);
    vector pointer = limit - cursor;      // limit, limit-1, ..., 0
    vector next = cursor + make_real(1.0);
    recur(next);
    return pointer;
}

function string main() { return "ok"; }
